05323nam a22006855i 9780226525495DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265254957 a10.7208/97802265254952doi  a(DE-B1597)522578  a(OCoLC)1015676187  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aLC2731b.D37 2018eb 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a371.829/960732231 aDarby, Derrick, eauthor.14aThe Color of Mind :bWhy the Origins of the Achievement Gap Matter for Justice /cDerrick Darby, John L. Rury. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b2 halftones, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory and Philosophy of Education Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. What School Leaders Need to Know -- tONE. The Racial Achievement Gap -- tTWO. The Color of Mind: Constructing Racial Differences in Intellect, Character, and Conduct -- tTHREE. The Color of Schooling: Constructing the Racial Achievement Gap -- tFOUR. Voices of Dissent: Dispelling an Inglorious Fallacy -- tFIVE. "A Tangle of Pathology": The Color of Mind Takes a Cultural Turn -- tSIX. What Schools Cannot Fix: Poverty, Inequality, and Segregation -- tSEVEN. Old Poison in New Bottles: How the Color of Mind Thrives in Schools and Affects Achievement -- tEIGHT. Why We Sort Kids in School -- tNINE. Unjust Schools: Why the Origins of the Achievement Gap Matter -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican students vary in educational achievement, but white students in general typically have better test scores and grades than black students. Why is this the case, and what can school leaders do about it? In The Color of Mind, Derrick Darby and John L. Rury answer these pressing questions and show that we cannot make further progress in closing the achievement gap until we understand its racist origins. Telling the story of what they call the Color of Mind-the idea that there are racial differences in intelligence, character, and behavior-they show how philosophers, such as David Hume and Immanuel Kant, and American statesman Thomas Jefferson, contributed to the construction of this pernicious idea, how it influenced the nature of schooling and student achievement, and how voices of dissent such as Frederick Douglass, Frances Ellen Watkins Harper, and W. E. B. Du Bois debunked the Color of Mind and worked to undo its adverse impacts. Rejecting the view that racial differences in educational achievement are a product of innate or cultural differences, Darby and Rury uncover the historical interplay between ideas about race and American schooling, to show clearly that the racial achievement gap has been socially and institutionally constructed. School leaders striving to bring justice and dignity to American schools today must work to root out the systemic manifestations of these ideas within schools, while still doing what they can to mitigate the negative effects of poverty, segregation, inequality, and other external factors that adversely affect student achievement. While we cannot expect schools alone to solve these vexing social problems, we must demand that they address the dignitary injustices associated with how we track, discipline, and deal with special education that reinforce long-standing racist ideas. That is the only way to expel the Color of Mind from schools, close the racial achievement gap, and afford all children the dignity they deserve.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAcademic achievementxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aAfrican AmericansxEducationzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in educationzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aSocial justicezUnited States. 4aColor of Mind index. 4aColor of Mind. 4aachievement gap. 4adignity. 4ajustice. 4aopportunity gap. 4arace. 4aracism. 4aschool discipline. 4aspecial education. 4atracking. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aRury, John L., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226525495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226525495.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles